NATION; 
</P>
<P>
WATCH THIEVES USE CHAIN SAW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
UNION GAP, Wash. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two holdup men used a chain saw to cut off the left hand of an out-of-work 
migrant farm worker to steal his expensive watch and two rings, police said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
"They did it for the sheer joy of doing it. 
</P>
<P>
That kind of random violence is frightening," Police Chief Lane Roberts said. 
</P>
<P>
The victim, a 20-year-old believed to be from Mexico, was listed in stable 
condition at Yakima Valley Memorial Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
The victim told police he and his cousin were at a grocery store Friday in this 
Yakima suburb and were approached by two men who offered to sell them a chain 
saw. One of the men pulled a gun, and the two victims were forced into their 
own car and driven to a remote area, where the holdup men tried to remove the 
victim's jewelry. 
</P>
<P>
The man's watch, valued at $1,500, had a special security latch that was 
difficult to open. The victim tried to show the robbers how to remove the 
watch, but they apparently "saw this as resistance and took the most expedient 
method to get to it," Roberts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
