<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHORT TAKES; 
</P>
<P>
BACALL: BROADWAY'S APPEAL LOST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PORT HURON, Mich. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tony Award-winning actress Lauren Bacall says the theater is still her first 
love, but Broadway just isn't the same anymore and she'd rather work in smaller 
venues outside New York. 
</P>
<P>
Bacall complained during a talk at Town Hall here Monday that Broadway's 
emphasis on reviving old hits in recent years has limited opportunities for 
actors. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm tired of revivals. I would rather be on stage in Chicago or in a good 
repertory theater in Seattle than be doing some of the things available on 
Broadway," she said. 
</P>
<P>
Bacall, who won Tonys for "Applause" and "Woman of the Year," credited her late 
husband Humphrey Bogart for her success. He starred opposite her in her first 
movie, "To Have and Have Not," in 1944. 
</P>
<P>
"Bogie was the best teacher I had," she said. "He showed me the ropes. Until I 
met him, I believed everything I read." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Lauren Bacall 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
