<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: SANTA ANA; 
</P>
<P>
CANDIDATE DEFENDS HIRING OF DETECTIVE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LILY ENG 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
City Council candidate Coween Dickerson Tuesday defended the actions of her 
former campaign treasurer in hiring a private detective to trail Councilman 
Miguel A. Pulido Jr. to find out whether he lives in the city. 
</P>
<P>
But Dickerson said at a press conference that she had accepted the resignation 
of the treasurer, Salvador Juarez, saying he should have informed her of his 
actions. 
</P>
<P>
Dickerson, a self-employed business analyst, said that Juarez was trying to 
"act responsibly" in attempting to determine whether Pulido actually lives in 
Santa Ana. 
</P>
<P>
"I don't think he did anything wrong," Dickerson said of Juarez, "but he should 
have asked me. I would have told him not to." 
</P>
<P>
Dickerson said that Juarez offered to resign last Thursday and that Zeke 
Hernandez, who lost to Pulido in the 1986 council race, will be her new 
treasurer. 
</P>
<P>
Hiring a detective, Dickerson said, was a "waste of money." She asserted that 
it is common knowledge that Pulido lived outside Santa Ana. Dickerson, who has 
made this a campaign issue, added that none of her campaign money was used for 
the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
Pulido maintains that he has lived in Santa Ana in a rented room since 1986, 
when he first ran for office. He described Juarez's resignation as "too little 
and too late." Dickerson and her supporters, he said, were making Juarez the 
"fall guy" for the "mistake of hiring an investigator." 
</P>
<P>
"If she can't control the activity of her own treasurer," Pulido said, "how 
could she purport to be a council person who's going to have a whole city under 
her responsibility?" 
</P>
<P>
Private investigator William Holland of Fountain Valley said Juarez hired him 
in August to determine whether Pulido was actually living in Fullerton at his 
family's home before moving to a house on Garnsey Street in Santa Ana last 
month. Holland said he has submitted his report to the district attorney's 
office. He said that Juarez paid him with his own checks. 
</P>
<P>
Deputy Dist. Atty. Wallace J. Wade said the office is reviewing the report. 
LILY ENG 
</P>
</TEXT>
